# <%= @app %> — agent guide

This is a **shaolin** app: a modular CQRS/Event-Sourcing backend. Each entity is a self-contained
module under `app/modules/<name>/` you can own and change in isolation.

## Conventions (deterministic — generate, don't hand-wire)

```
bundle exec shaolin g module <plural-name>          # plain CRUD module (boots immediately)
bundle exec shaolin g module <plural-name> --es     # event-sourced CQRS module (opt in to ES)
bundle exec shaolin server                          # serve HTTP (Falcon) on $PORT (8080)
bundle exec shaolin console                         # IRB with the app booted
bundle exec shaolin describe --json                 # machine-readable map of all modules
bundle exec shaolin lint                            # check module isolation (no cross-module reach-ins)
bundle exec shaolin graph                           # module dependency graph
bundle exec shaolin projections rebuild             # rebuild read models by replaying events
```

A **CRUD** module (default) contains: `<entity>.rb` (ActiveRecord model) · `dto/` (boundary
validation) · `controllers/` (HTTP → model) · `db/migrate/` · `CONTRACT.md` (the module's public
boundary — read this first). An **`--es`** module adds the CQRS/ES anatomy: `commands/` (typed
intent) · `events/` (domain events) · `<entity>.rb` as an event-sourced aggregate ·
`command_handlers/` · `projections/` (update read models) · `read_models/` · `queries/`.

## Flow

`HTTP → DTO validate → command → aggregate emits event → event store (Postgres) → projection →
read model → query`. Write and read are separated (CQRS); state is event-sourced.

## Rules for changing a module

- Stay inside one module folder; cross-module access only via declared `imports`/`exports` in
  `module.rb`.
- Reference sibling files with explicit `require_relative`.
- Add fields by editing the command, event, DTO, aggregate, projection, read-model migration.
- Run `bundle exec rspec` after changes.

Read `CONTRACT.md` in any module to understand it without opening its internals.
